{"page_content": "In addition, you need to understand not just how to use the tools presented in this\nbook in isolation, but how they can work together to solve a larger problem. Some\u2010\ntimes the data is easily available and well formatted, allowing a simple scraper to do\nthe trick. Other times you have to put some thought into it.\nIn Chapter 11, for example, you combined the Selenium library to identify Ajax-\nloaded images on Amazon and Tesseract to use OCR to read them. In the Six Degrees\nof Wikipedia problem, you used regular expressions to write a crawler that stored link\ninformation in a database, and then used a graph-solving algorithm in order to\nanswer the question, \u201cWhat is the shortest path of links between Kevin Bacon and\nEric Idle?\u201d\nThere is rarely an unsolvable problem when it comes to automated data collection on\nthe internet. Just remember: the internet is one giant API with a somewhat poor user\ninterface.\nMoving Forward \n| \n277", "metadata": {"producer": "Antenna House PDF Output Library 6.2.609 (Linux64)", "creator": "AH CSS Formatter V6.2 MR4 for Linux64 : 6.2.6.18551 (2014/09/24 15:00JST)", "creationdate": "2018-03-21T11:42:51+00:00", "source": "D:\\Users\\wpoga\\Documents\\Ebooks\\Antigravity Library\\Web Scraping with Python, 2nd Edition.pdf", "file_path": "D:\\Users\\wpoga\\Documents\\Ebooks\\Antigravity Library\\Web Scraping with Python, 2nd Edition.pdf", "total_pages": 306, "format": "PDF 1.6", "title": "Web Scraping with Python", "author": "Ryan Mitchell", "subject": "", "keywords": "", "moddate": "2018-06-03T19:49:15-08:00", "trapped": "", "modDate": "D:20180603194915-08'00'", "creationDate": "D:20180321114251Z", "page": 294}, "type": "Document"}
